<subSubSection id="2A53F2944A094B5D58FAFAB116879039" pageId="0" pageNumber="22396" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="06CB4D75494B10EA58420F54367FBF94" pageId="0" pageNumber="22396">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C2F22A6A91C809B3F51636AC474DB2BF" pageId="0" pageNumber="22396">
There are a small number of minute, limuloid phorid genera in the world. In the New World tropics, the only relatively similar genera have large, differentiated frontal setae that are several times longer than the short frontal setae and do not have the scutellum covering the abdomen (
<bibRefCitation id="2183AE66D477DC7E35E4D96CE9CEA3EF" author="Brown, B. V." journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="22396" pagination="115 - 137" title="Convergent adaptations in Phoridae (Diptera) living in the nests of social insects: a review of the New World Aenigmatiinae" volume="165" year="1993">Brown 1993</bibRefCitation>
). The Old World species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A24FFCC014B8D1356296A77F8D1FD7F5" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Euryplatea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Euryplatea" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="22396" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Euryplatea</taxonomicName>
Schmitz, likewise differ by having the abdomen not covered by the scutellum and by having a solid, triangular wing rudiment (
<bibRefCitation id="D8FB9A416992C99A0AABEC967A30E8FF" author="Brown, B. V." journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="22396" pagination="550 - 554" title="Small size no protection for acrobat ants: world's smallest fly is a parasitic phorid (Diptera: Phoridae)" volume="105" year="2012">Brown 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
